FUNctionally Fit?
.
.
Pun on words, but does your fitness regime include functional movements to get you “prime time ready” for your activities of daily living? Is it fun 🤩 & enjoyable? Are you seeing results?

Enough with the questions, now ponder the facts and possible answers! We had to crawl before we walked upright. Going back to the foundations of human movement is key 🔑 Crawling includes:

✅ Bodyweight utilization
✅ Multi-planar movements
✅ Stabilization & Mobilization
✅ Flexibility
✅ Core 
✅ Locomotion

Get down all 4s, get back to where it all started, your body and muscle memory is intact. No better way to evaluate joint mobility (fingers, wrists, elbows, knees), loading the body in a stress free environment, other than your weight. Crawl forward, crawl back; straighten things, bend, push, pull, twist, kick, rotate. Explore. Investigate. Evaluate. What’s tight? What challenges you? What’s a piece of cake?

This simple and straight forward routine I’m demoing could be a great warm-up, cooldown or even recovery interval in any HIIT, Cardio, or strength training workout. Most of all it’s FUN. Great for all demographics, and can be altered w/ modifications & amplifications.

Shoutouts to programs and modalities such as TRX Training & Animal Flow that incorporate Bodyweight training as the foundation of their programming.

Get back to the basics of what makes your fit time FUNctional! Do you incorporate these moves in your current workout 🏋️‍♀️? Drop me a line ⬇️ 
.
.
.
.

Tight shoulders, try this 👇🏽 
.
.
I was diagnosed with Spinal Scoliosis (side to side curvature of the spine) in high school. I vowed to stand tall no matter what the odds.

Enter PILATES. Pilates is definitely revered as a coveted way to strengthen the core with the classical series of exercises, by Mr. Joseph himself, I’m finding the mobility portion of the practice to be equally satisfying in my weekly practice to conquer my scoliosis.

Ultimately CORE work is meant to strengthen and lengthen the spine in all means possible, but today’s typical work day as in more of an immobilized state than ever before. Technology has us hunched over more than ever before and I’m not about to become a goner of the hunchback group. Add to it age related wear and tear (Spinal Stenosis) and prevention is imperative. The thoracic portion of the spine takes a beating in this regard. 

The thoracic spine is the longest region of the spine (T1-T12 vertebrae) and by some measures is also the most complex. Connecting with the cervical spine above and the lumbar spine below, the thoracic spine runs from the base of the neck down to the abdomen. It is the only spinal region attached to the rib cage. Create some mobility in your CORE which will opt to improve strength.

Try these series of mobility exercises, lie sideways on the floor, knees bent, heels, hips & shoulders aligned. Legs don’t move. 3 reps of each, switch sides.

Windshield Wiper Arms:
1️⃣ Elbows Bent- fix lower arm and rotate upper arm until shoulder blades touch the floor
2️⃣ Arms Straight- same as above
3️⃣ Top Shoulder Reach- top arm reaches forward of lower arm

Feel the relief through your rib cage, pelvis & lower back! Tag someone in this post who can benefit from this simple practice.

The answer is…
.

Single arms or both? Both! Bilateral and unilateral training are beneficial for a variety of reasons…
1️⃣ Balanced Training Philosophy- we’re all either left side or right side dominant, unless you are ambidextrous. Condition & train things independently and then wreak the rewards when you workout both together 💪🏽
2️⃣ Injury Prevention. Synergistic dominance can lead to movement imperfections when we favor one side over the other. 
3️⃣ Break Plateaus. Variety, intensity and variation lead to continued success in meeting your fitness goals.
.
TRX training is a great way to utilize this training philosophy. Grab your suspension trainer and your own and let’s vibe. Strengthen your entire core and body.

What’s your right fit?
.
Fitting in ?
Fitting the standard ?
Fitting societal acceptance ?
Fitting the rules and regs ?
Fitting the “look” and “vibe?
.
.
How about what “fits you”? Exercise and fitness can be tricky, amidst the hoopala of what’s trending and popular, sometimes we’re bombarded with so much pressure to conform, we lose track of what matters most. What serves you best? It’s not selfish in the grand scheme, all boils down to self care. What next?
.
Questions to ask yourself:
1️⃣ What are your short term and long range goals? Weight loss? Stamina & Strength? Increasing bone density? Doesn’t have to be one, could be several. You get to decide. 
2️⃣ How you feel vs how you look? This can be triggering, how about focusing on how you feel “physically” from your fitness experience(s) vs the “visual” representation! Tapping into what you need physically, mentally and emotionally of how we approach our fit regime will ultimately support the latter. Mindset is a medium for success.
3️⃣ Do you have a support network to substantiate your goals and a game plan in order to garner success. Are you a loan wolf 🐺and crush things independently or will group fitness and/ or working with a personal trainer keep you accountable. Maybe it’s nutritional advice, and that may be the missing link. It’s not just the destination, but journey. Resource what you need.
.
Do you… you can change your mind as many times as you like. There are no set rules. Settle into the moment and access what “you need”. Showing up for yourself first, is a true gift, that uniqueness is your transparency to being true to yourself. 
.
.
.
.
.
#fitspo #fitspiration #fitnessjourney #mindset #fitnessaffirmations #crushit

Try this shoulder 🔥 burner 👇🏽 
.
.
Supersets are designed to break strength plateaus, increase lean muscle maturity and optimize your workout 🏋️‍♀️ time efficiently. Tap into second stage muscle failure (it’s the shakes, only after you’ve survived first stage- the lactic acid burn) and see the results level up fast 💪🏽.

Chose 3 sets of dumbbells that increase incrementally. The regime consists of back to back sets that ladder 🪜 up and down with weight and reps incrementally (as the weight increases reps decrease and vice versa. If you’re in the endurance phase of programming stick to reps of 10-12-15, strength: 6-8-10 consecutively. 1 set consists of: Ladder up, recover, ladder down. I use this protocol during my shoulder training sessions and have seen serious results in my strength gains, but also size and definition 🏆 

⭐️Example of what I do and use- Dumbbell Medial Deltoid Lateral Raise
▶️Weights: 10, 12, & 15 pound dumbbells
▶️ 3-4 Sets of the following -
➡️ Set 1:
✅ 10# dumbbells for 15 reps
✅ 12# dumbbells for 12 reps
✅ 15# dumbbells for 10 reps
❌ Recover 60sec
✅ 15# dumbbells for 10 reps
✅ 12# dumbbells for 12 reps
✅ 10# dumbbells for 15 reps
❌ Recover 60sec

Off to Set 2….

I guarantee you’ll see results and this is a phenomenal way to end any strength training session, satisfied and challenged. Could do it with any other muscle group scenario or exercise: chest press, bicep curls, squats, etc.

Try it and let me know how it goes… drop your questions or comments below 👇🏽 3 cheers for your strength gains crew 🙌🏽

Like the Pilates Reformer? Try these 👇🏽 
.
.
It was love ❤️ at first try for me with the Pilates Reformer…There’s no denying the multiple benefits of a reformer workout: postural improvements, decreased back pain, core strength. But like you, I don’t have the space at home to accommodate a machine or the time in my schedule to always attend a class, so… I’ve found these Pilates ball exercises equally comparable to the ass kickin’ 🍑 from the Reformer.

The Pilates ball offers convenience, it adds support yet instability, and it comes in a variety of cool 😎 colors and easy to tote in your bag, deflate and inflate when ready. Try this series of hard core 6 pack of exercises on for size and challenge your limits…

1️⃣Plank Pushup + Crunch
2️⃣Twisted Plank Extension R/L
3️⃣Side Plank Thread the Needle R/L
4️⃣Hamstring Curls
5️⃣Frogger + Scissor Kicks
6️⃣Spinal Extension + Teaser Circle
▶️ Perform each exercise for 1 minute and flow to the next w/ quick transition time. Make note of the moves done on 1 side of the body, since these are unilateral, you’ll need to repeat the circuit twice to complete both sides. Complete the circuit, resting minimally for 30-60sec. 
🤔 Ultimate kickass challenge, repeat it 4x. 

Go super slow, challenge your muscular endurance and slow twitch muscle fibers, feel the burn 🔥 and feel your muscles shake. Like ❤️ Share ✈️ Save🎀 or Tag someone who digs PILATES or could benefit from these fitness tips…

Who says you need to touch your toes?

Yes, touching your toes is great. It promotes lengthening your hamstrings, and posterior chain to accommodate the stretch, which feels great for all us computer 💻 workers bees 🐝 Your back will thank you in the long run. 

How about, instead, extending back and touching your heel? The benefit? 

1️⃣ Spinal Extension- great for those intervertebral spaces. In English, it means creating space in your spinal column. With technology making us hunker down 24/7, why not reverse the effects.
2️⃣ Balance- wtf, it’s a hard move to do. Get your agility & coordination prepared for this one ☝🏽 you’ll wobble at first but w/ practice you’ll be crushing it.
3️⃣ Hip Mobility- open your hips… period! Tight hip flexors can also be a culprit in poor posture and back pain. Level up with something new. 

Try it… you’ll like it. Split your stance, secure the feet, back heel lifted. Reach back and touch your heel, stand back upright again. Maybe 4-8 reps preside to start, 1-2 sets. Progress from here.

Happy Mobility Monday rockstars… let me know how it goes👇🏽 Check out this new Monday feature on my feed.

Desk job got you tight & shit?
.
.
Technology got your posture in a quandary? Try this simple and effective mobility move and see and feel the difference. Hop up on your desk and get your work colleagues talking… really, you just need an elevated base. 

1️⃣ Plant your feet wide. Secure your footing and squat deep. This promotes ankle, knee and hip mobility (triple flexion in fitness terms ✅).
2️⃣ Hold a weighted object in your hands. A dumbbell, light kettlebell or even your work bag/briefcase will do! Hold it directly in front of your chest to start. 
3️⃣ From here, notice I reach towards the floor. This tractions (creates space) in the spinal column and allows back muscles to lengthen. Keep your glutes engaged, back flat, and shoulder blades drawn in. Return to seated position.

Repeat 2-4 times. Great break during your work day from the computer, phone, or too much time in the 🚗 Your body will thank you 🙏 Save this and try it or share it with someone in need 🙌🏽

Shoulders tight? Try this 👇🏽

Technically, this move promotes thoracic rotation of the spine (movement around the shoulder blades) which gets little to no movement thanks to technology sometimes 📱 🖥️ so… try this simple and effective mobility move and see and feel the difference. Breast Care Awareness for dudes👇🏽 
.
.
Although rare, men can get breast cancer! Statistics show that 1 out of every 100 breast cancers diagnosed in the US is found in a man‼️ Now that I’ve got your attention, let’s chat types, symptoms…

Types:
The most common kinds of breast cancer in men are—
* Invasive ductal carcinoma. The cancer cells begin in the ducts and then grow outside the ducts into other parts of the breast tissue. Invasive cancer cells can also spread, or metastasize, to other parts of the body.
* Ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) is a breast disease that may lead to invasive breast cancer. The cancer cells are only in the lining of the ducts, and have not spread to other tissues in the breast.

What Are the Symptoms?
The most common symptoms of breast cancer in men are—
* A lump or swelling in the breast.
* Redness or flaky skin in the breast.
* Irritation or dimpling of breast skin.
* Nipple discharge.
* Pulling in of the nipple or pain in the nipple area.
These symptoms can happen with other conditions that are not cancer. If you have any symptoms or changes, see your doctor right away.

More Breast Care Awareness for dudes👇🏽 
.
.
Part 2 as promised. This post, Risk Factors, here’s the 411. Although rare, men can get breast cancer! Statistics show that 1 out of every 100 breast cancers diagnosed in the US is found in a man‼️ 

What Are the Risk Factors?
Several factors can increase a man’s chance of getting breast cancer.

👉🏽 Getting older. The risk for breast cancer increases with age. Most breast cancers are found after age 50.
👉🏽 Genetic mutations. Inherited changes (mutations) in certain genes, such as BRCA1 and BRCA2, increase breast cancer risk.
👉🏽 Family history of breast cancer. A man’s risk for breast cancer is higher if a close family member has had breast cancer.
👉🏽 Radiation therapy treatment. Men who had radiation therapy to the chest have a higher risk of getting breast cancer.
👉🏽 Hormone therapy treatment. Drugs containing estrogen (a hormone that helps develop and maintain female sex characteristics), which were used to treat prostate cancer in the past, increase men’s breast cancer risk.
👉🏽 Klinefelter syndrome. Klinefelter syndrome is a rare genetic condition in which a male has an extra X chromosome. This can lead to the body making higher levels of estrogen and lower levels of androgens (hormones that help develop and maintain male sex characteristics).
👉🏽 Certain conditions that affect the testicles can increase breast cancer risk.
👉🏽 Liver disease. Cirrhosis (scarring) of the liver can lower androgen levels and raise estrogen levels in men, increasing the risk of breast cancer.
👉🏽 Overweight and obesity. Older men who are overweight or have obesity have a higher risk of getting breast cancer than men at a normal weight.

Detection and treatment are key. Part 3, next post, reducing risk factors/ treatment… be in the know my friends… exercise is always a great preventative, grab your TRX Bandit and let’s go!

More 411 Breast Care Awareness for dudes👇🏽 
.
.
Part 3 as promised. This post, reducing risk factors and treatment. Although rare, men can get breast cancer! Statistics show that 1 out of every 100 breast cancers diagnosed in the US is found in a man‼️ 

What Can I Do to Reduce My Risk?
If several members of your family have had breast or ovarian cancer, or one of your family members has a known BRCA1 or BRCA2 mutation, share this information with your doctor. Your doctor may refer you for genetic counseling. In men, mutations in the BRCA1 and BRCA2 genes can increase the risk of breast cancer, high-grade prostate cancer, and pancreatic cancer. If genetic testing shows that you have a BRCA1 or BRCA2 gene mutation, your doctor will explain what you should do to find cancer early, if you get it.

How Is Breast Cancer Treated?
As in women, treatment for breast cancer in men depends on how big the tumor is and how far it has spread. Treatment may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, hormone therapy, and targeted therapy. For more information, see the National Cancer Institute’s Male Breast Cancer Treatment.

Detection and treatment are key. Be in the know my friends… exercise is always a great preventative, grab your TRX Suspension Trainer and try this Single Leg Plank Crunch:
1️⃣ Adjust straps so foot cradles are mid-calf length.
2️⃣ Ground based, face away from the anchor point and slide 1 foot through the foot cradles.
3️⃣ Start in a high plank position, shoulders & hips square.
4️⃣ Draw both knees into the forearms, rainbow round through the back, stop when knees are under the hips. Resist rotation.
5️⃣ Return to plank position.
*️⃣ Perform 12-15 reps per leg. Great for contralateral training (cross body effect).
